library(ggplot2)

Analysis for each variable

We start extracting the main characteristics from each variable.

Survival Chances -> Survived (0 = No; 1 = Yes)

summary(titanic.train$Survived)
  0   1 
412 256 
round(prop.table(table(titanic.train$Survived)),3)  #me make the prop table and summaries like in the lab sessions

    0     1 
0.617 0.383 
ggplot(titanic.train)+
  geom_bar(aes(x = Survived, fill = Sex), alpha=0.8)+  labs(title="Survival rates", #we plot some of the results and make                                                                                                it look understandable
       x="Survived?",
       y="N of passengers") +
  scale_fill_brewer(palette = "Set1")+
  theme_minimal()+
  scale_x_discrete(labels=c("Died", "Survived"))

We can ensure that the 61.7% of the passengers couldnt finish the trip while the other 38.3% could. After plotting the survival rates, we use the command fill to see how its influenced by gender noticing that the passengers who survived the most were women.

Passenger Class -> Pclass (1 st class, 2 nd class, 3 rd class)

table(titanic.train$Pclass)

round(prop.table(table(titanic.train$Pclass)),3)            #we repeat the same methodology, no explanation needed

    1     2     3

ggplot(titanic.train)+
  geom_bar(aes(x = Pclass, fill=Sex), alpha=0.8)+  
  labs(title="Class Passengers", 
       x="",
       y="N of passengers") +
  scale_fill_brewer(palette = "Set1")+
  theme_minimal()+
  scale_x_discrete(labels=c("1st Class", "2nd Class","3rd Class"))

We conclude that there were more passengers in 3rd class and highlight that in this class, there are a lot of men. This may help us to formulate some questions in a near future.

Age -> Passengers age

summary(titanic.train$Age)
   Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
   0.42   22.00   28.00   29.15   35.00   74.00 
ggplot(titanic.train)+
  geom_histogram(aes(x = Age, fill=Sex), alpha=0.8)+  
  labs(title="Passengers Age", 
       x="Age",
       y="N of passengers") +
  scale_fill_brewer(palette = "Set1")+
  theme_minimal()

We observe how the age is distributed among the passengers and sex, highlighting that there were more men than women. The mean age was around 29 years old and the older passenger was 74 years old. To appreciate a little bit better this variable we create a boxplot.

ggplot(titanic.train)+
  geom_boxplot(aes(x = Age, fill=Sex), alpha=0.8)+  
  labs(title="Age vs Sex", 
       x="Age",
       y="") +
  scale_fill_brewer(palette = "Set1")+
  theme_minimal()+
  coord_flip()+
  theme(axis.text.x = element_blank())

We can see better the results of the summary command in this plot. Noticing some outliers, which may be interesting to navigate through while answering some questions, and that men and women had similar ages.

Our questions

While analyzing all the variables we came up with the following questions, we will answer them one by one.

1.- Passengers survived depending on which class they had?

ggplot(titanic.train)+
  geom_bar(aes( x = Survived, fill = Pclass),position=position_dodge(), alpha=0.8)+  
  labs(title="Survival vs Class", 
       x="",
       fill="Class",
       y="N of Passengers") +
  scale_fill_brewer(palette = "Set2", labels = c("1st Class", "2nd CLass", "3rd Class"))+ 
  theme_minimal()+
  scale_x_discrete(labels=c("Died", "Survived"))

If we have a look at this plot, we can see how people in 3rd class were less likely to survive after the incident. Despite the fact that the 3rd class was formed by the majority of the passengers. In addition, people traveling in first class were more likely to survive, if we compare the ratios.

2.- The passengers who paid more than 100 pounds for a ticket survived? What about who paid the most?

Consequently, we now focus on what we highlighted during the analysis of each variable. We want to see what happened with people who paid a lot.

m <- which(titanic.train$Fare >= 100)                 #we filter the data to obtain people who paid more than 100 pounds
m<- titanic.train[m,]                                 #m is our "aux"
m

ggplot(m)+
  geom_bar(aes(x = Survived, fill=Sex), alpha=0.8)+  
  labs(title="Expensive tickets payers", 
       x="Survived?",
       y="N of Passengers") +
  scale_fill_brewer(palette = "Set1")+ 
  theme_minimal()+
  scale_x_discrete(labels=c("Died", "Survived"))

Unlike we saw on the first survival rate plot, the people who paid the most had a better chance of surviving than the rest of the passengers. We believe that women had more survival chances than men not depending on the class in which they traveled. We also highlight that in first, there was a similar number of men and women.

3.- How many kids and old people survived comparing them with other age ranges? Does their embarking class had anything to do with it?

We will first create a new row to the dataframe, where we will segregate children (passengers younger than 18), adults (from 19 to 39, people older than 40 are not old but looking to the age range in the passengers we needed some more data) and elder people (more than 40 years old).

young <- which(titanic.train$Age <= 18)
adult <- which(titanic.train$Age > 18 & titanic.train$Age<=39)            #we filter Ages by ranges
old <- which(titanic.train$Age >= 40)

y <- rep("Young", length(young))
young <- titanic.train[young,]                                          #we add a column with the label young, old or adult
young <- cbind(young, "A" = y)

a <- rep("Adult", length(adult))
adult <- titanic.train[adult,]
adult <- cbind(adult, "A" =a)

o <- rep("Old", length(old))
old <- titanic.train[old,]
old <- cbind(old, "A" =o)



df2<-data.frame()
df2 <- rbind(df2, young, adult, old)                                    #this will help us to use the fill command in ggplot
df2
                                                                        #and consequently obtain a better plot

ggplot(df2)+
  geom_bar(aes(Survived, fill=A), alpha=0.8)+  
  labs(title="Survival by age ranges", 
       x="Survived?",
       fill="Age Group",
       y="N of Passengers") +
  scale_fill_brewer(palette = "Paired")+ 
  theme_minimal()+
  scale_x_discrete(labels=c("Died", "Survived"))


ggplot(df2)+
  geom_bar(aes(Pclass, fill=A), alpha=0.8)+  
  labs(title="Embarking Class by age ranges", 
       x="",
       fill="Age Group",
       y="N of Passengers") +
  scale_fill_brewer(palette = "Paired")+ 
  theme_minimal()+
  scale_x_discrete(labels=c("1st Class", "2nd Class", "3rd Class"))

On the first plot we can observe that young people had a 50% chance of survival, meanwhile old people had less chances of survival and adults had even less chance. Focusing on their boarding class, we see that many old people traveling in first class survived, we believe that its due to the fact that they were in the most expensive class.

4.- Is there any relation between the embarking port and survival chances?

ggplot(titanic.train)+
  geom_bar(aes(x=Survived, fill=Embarked), alpha=0.8)+  
  labs(title="Embarking Port and Survival Chances", 
       x="",
       fill="Embarking port",
       y="N of Passengers") +
  scale_fill_brewer(palette = "OrRd",labels = c("Cherbourg", "Queenstown", "Southampton"))+ 
  theme_minimal()+
  scale_x_discrete(labels=c("Died", "Survived"))

We thought that the probabilty of survival shouldve been similar among the ports but we noticed that when embarking in Cherbourg had slightly greater chances of survival.

5.- Having children increases your chances of survival?

ch <- which(titanic.train$Parch >0)                                         #more filters
ch <- titanic.train[ch,]
ggplot(titanic.train)+
  geom_bar(aes(x = Parch, fill=Survived))+  
  labs(title="Children and Survival Chances", 
       x="N of children or parents",
       y="N of Passengers") +
  scale_fill_brewer(palette = "YlGnBu", labels = c("Died", "Survived"))+ 
  theme_minimal()

If we compare the number of people who didnt have children or parents we surprisingly observe that had less chance of survival. This could be due to the lack of observations from passengers with children, as the vast mayority of them didnt have children.

6.- How where fares computed? What influences the price, the class, the port or the passengers gender?

c <- which(titanic.train$Embarked == "C")
q <- which(titanic.train$Embarked == "Q")                         #filtering by where the port was
s <- which(titanic.train$Embarked == "S")

c <- titanic.train[c,]
q <- titanic.train[q,]                                            #obtain filtered data
s <- titanic.train[s,]

df <- data.frame(mean(c$Fare),mean(q$Fare),mean(s$Fare))          #we make a table with the mean price for each filtered port
colnames(df) <- c("Cherbourg", "Queenstown", "Southampton")
df

c <- which(titanic.train$Sex == "male")
q <- which(titanic.train$Sex == "female")

c <- titanic.train[c,]
q <- titanic.train[q,]


df <- data.frame(mean(c$Fare),mean(q$Fare))
colnames(df) <- c("Male Fare", "Female Fare")
df

ggplot(titanic.train)+
  geom_boxplot(aes(x = Fare, fill=Pclass), alpha=0.8)+  
  labs(title="Fare Prices", 
       fill="Class",
       x="Price in Pounds",
       y="") +
  scale_fill_brewer(palette = "Set2", labels = c("1st Class", "2nd CLass", "3rd Class"))+
  theme_minimal()+
  theme(axis.text.y = element_blank())

We conclude that the price was defined depending on the class you booked, 1st was the most expensive, not depending on the port you embarked, 2nd class fluctuated a little bit depending on where you embarked and 3rd class was constant; Cherbourg was the most expensive port in average, followed by Southampton and Queenstown which was 5 times cheaper. Moreover, we see that women paid a lot more than men but of course, gender didnt take part in the computation of fares we just wanted to show how data can be interpreted in many ways.
